================================================================================
3. FINDINGS
================================================================================

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FINDING-01 [CRITICAL]
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Title      : No input format abstraction — input is hardcoded to Markdown
Description: Every OutputStrategy passes "--from markdown" to pandoc as a
             literal string. The Config struct's `input` field is a raw file
             path with no type annotation. There is no InputFormat type, no
             detection of input format by file extension, and no mechanism for
             callers to declare "this is an RST/HTML/DOCX input file."
Impact     : Impossible to implement docx → pdf, html → pdf, epub → html, or
             any non-Markdown input without touching the internals of each
             strategy. The output strategy matrix (see Section 4) cannot be
             realised without this abstraction.
Root Cause : V1 scope assumption that input is always Markdown. The pandoc
             "--from markdown" flag is embedded in strategy render() calls
             rather than derived from config or input file metadata.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FINDING-02 [CRITICAL]
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Title      : No intermediate representation (IR) layer
Description: The pipeline passes raw text strings between transforms and
             strategies. There is no typed document IR (e.g. AST, structured
             content model) shared between the transform phase and the strategy
             phase. Each strategy independently re-parses or delegates to
             pandoc from scratch.
Impact     : Cross-format reuse of processed content is impossible. Two
             simultaneous outputs (e.g. html + pdf) each invoke pandoc
             separately on the original source, repeating all parsing and
             transformation work. A shared IR would enable single-parse,
             multi-output rendering and support richer semantic transforms
             that operate on structure rather than raw text.
Root Cause : String-passing pipeline was sufficient for the initial scope.
             Pandoc's own AST (JSON format) could serve as a pragmatic IR
             without introducing a new dependency.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FINDING-03 [WARNING]
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Title      : Pipeline::run_transforms() and TransformRegistry::with_fail_fast()
             are unused in the main code path
Description: The Pipeline struct exposes run_transforms() and run_steps() but
             commands/build.rs uses TransformRegistry::apply_all() directly and
             only calls Pipeline::run_steps() for rendering. The Pipeline
             struct's transform phase is entirely bypassed. Additionally,
             TransformRegistry::with_fail_fast() is declared pub but never
             called by production code — fail_fast defaults to true and is
             never overridden by the build command.
Impact     : Dead public API surface increases maintenance burden and creates
             confusion about the intended integration point. Callers who read
             the Pipeline API may attempt to use run_transforms() unaware that
             the build command doesn't go through it. The fail-fast toggle is a
             valuable feature that is effectively hidden.
Root Cause : The Pipeline and TransformRegistry were built as independent
             units; the build orchestration wires them together in an ad-hoc
             way rather than through a unified entry point.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FINDING-04 [WARNING]
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Title      : No plugin / extension system for user-defined transforms
Description: The Transform trait is defined in the core crate and transforms
             are hardcoded in register_transforms(). There is no mechanism for
             external crates or configuration-level extensions to register
             custom transforms without modifying the core source. The fail-fast
             / continue-on-failure mode demonstrates that the registry design is
             mature enough to support dynamic registration, but the entry point
             is not exposed.
Impact     : Users who need custom preprocessing (e.g. custom variable syntax,
             citation expansion, diagram-as-code pre-processing) must fork the
             project or maintain patches.
Root Cause : No external extension API designed yet. The Transform trait is
             pub, but register_transforms() is the only factory and is not
             configurable from renderflow.yaml.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FINDING-05 [WARNING]
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Title      : Output renders are sequential — no parallelism
Description: commands/build.rs iterates over config.outputs in a for loop,
             rendering each format sequentially. For a three-output config
             (html + pdf + docx) the total render time is the sum of all
             pandoc invocations rather than the maximum.
Impact     : Performance degrades linearly with the number of output formats.
             Pandoc invocations for independent output formats (e.g. html and
             docx) could be fully parallelised. This is especially impactful
             for PDF rendering via tectonic, which can take several seconds.
Root Cause : The initial sequential implementation is correct and simpler.
             Parallelism was deferred as a future optimisation.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FINDING-06 [WARNING]
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Title      : EmojiTransform replaces emoji with "[emoji]" placeholder
Description: The EmojiTransform converts emoji characters to the literal
             string "[emoji]". This is a lossy, destructive transform — the
             original emoji character is discarded and the placeholder is not
             semantically meaningful in most document contexts (HTML, DOCX).
             Pandoc supports emoji rendering natively via the --from flag or
             the `emoji` extension.
Impact     : Documents authored with emoji (increasingly common in technical
             writing) will produce unexpected "[emoji]" strings in all output
             formats. Users are unlikely to expect this behaviour.
Root Cause : The transform was likely implemented to handle PDF/LaTeX rendering
             where emoji require special handling. However, the current
             implementation is applied unconditionally to all output formats,
             including HTML where emoji render natively.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FINDING-07 [WARNING]
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Title      : Template system covers HTML only; PDF and DOCX templates not
             validated at initialisation
Description: init_tera() loads only *.html files from the templates directory.
             PdfStrategy uses a LaTeX template via pandoc --template, and
             DocxStrategy uses a reference DOCX via --reference-doc, but
             neither is pre-validated by the Tera engine. The early template
             warning in build.rs (checking tera.get_template_names()) only
             catches HTML template mismatches; missing PDF or DOCX templates
             are silently ignored until render time.
Impact     : A misconfigured PDF or DOCX template will not surface until pandoc
             is actually invoked, potentially after a long transform phase.
             The user experience could be improved with early validation of all
             template types.
Root Cause : Tera was chosen as the template engine for HTML, and its API was
             reused for early validation without considering that the other
             strategies use different template mechanisms.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FINDING-08 [MINOR]
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Title      : VariableSubstitutionTransform uses naive {{key}} regex matching
Description: The variable substitution transform performs simple string search-
             and-replace using {{key}} patterns without considering Markdown
             context. A variable reference inside a fenced code block or an
             inline code span will be substituted, which may corrupt examples
             or documentation that legitimately contain {{...}} syntax.
Impact     : Documents that contain code examples with template-like syntax
             (e.g. Go templates, Helm charts, Jinja2 examples) will have those
             examples corrupted during variable substitution.
Root Cause : Simple implementation. Context-aware substitution requires either
             a Markdown parser or a two-pass approach that skips code spans.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FINDING-09 [MINOR]
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Title      : PandocStep is defined but not used in the primary build path
Description: src/pipeline/pandoc_step.rs defines a PandocStep struct that
             wraps pandoc invocations as a PipelineStep. However, the build
             command uses OutputStrategy implementations (HtmlStrategy,
             PdfStrategy, DocxStrategy) via StrategyStep, not PandocStep.
             PandocStep appears to be an earlier iteration of the strategy
             execution mechanism.
Impact     : Dead code increases codebase size and creates confusion about
             which abstraction is canonical for pandoc invocations.
Root Cause : Architectural iteration — the strategy pattern superseded the
             direct PandocStep approach but the old code was not removed.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FINDING-10 [MINOR]
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Title      : No caching of transform outputs between output formats
Description: For a config with multiple output formats, the full transform
             pipeline (emoji, variable substitution, syntax highlight) is
             executed once per output format. Since transforms are pure
             functions of the same input content and the same config variables,
             the output is identical for every format.
Impact     : Redundant CPU work proportional to the number of output formats.
             For large documents with many transforms this is wasteful.
Root Cause : The current loop structure (for output in &config.outputs)
             re-creates and re-runs the transform registry for each output
             rather than caching the transform result and reusing it.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FINDING-11 [MINOR]
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Title      : README lists Tera/Jinja2 templates as a feature but omits DOCX
Description: The README Features section lists "Custom templates — Per-output
             Jinja2-compatible templates via Tera" but does not mention DOCX
             reference-doc support. The Supported Output Types table shows only
             html and pdf, omitting docx (which is now fully implemented and
             tested). The Roadmap still lists "DOCX output format" as pending.
Impact     : User-facing documentation does not reflect the current capabilities
             of the system, which may cause confusion or undersell the tool.
Root Cause : Documentation was not updated when DOCX support was implemented.

