5. ADDITIONAL OUTPUT FORMAT SUGGESTIONS
================================================================================

The following formats are recommended as high-value additions to Renderflow,
ordered by implementation complexity and user demand.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FORMAT-01: EPUB (Priority P1)
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Rationale   : EPUB is the standard format for e-books and long-form technical
              documentation. pandoc supports md → epub3 natively.
Dependencies: pandoc (already required)
Config type : epub
Pandoc flags: --from markdown -o output.epub --epub-cover-image=cover.png
Template    : --epub-metadata (XML), CSS stylesheet
Complexity  : Low — single pandoc invocation, no additional engine

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FORMAT-02: LaTeX Source (Priority P1)
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Rationale   : Publishing workflows frequently require LaTeX source for journal
              submission (arXiv, academic publishers). Rendering to .tex (not
              .pdf) allows further manual editing.
Dependencies: pandoc (already required)
Config type : latex
Pandoc flags: --from markdown -o output.tex
Template    : pandoc LaTeX templates or custom .tex header
Complexity  : Low — no additional engine; LaTeX template support via --template

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FORMAT-03: Reveal.js Slides (Priority P2)
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Rationale   : Slide decks from Markdown are popular in developer/technical
              communities. Reveal.js produces interactive browser-based slides
              from pandoc's revealjs output format.
Dependencies: pandoc; reveal.js CDN or local install
Config type : revealjs
Pandoc flags: -t revealjs --standalone -o output.html
Template    : Custom reveal.js theme CSS
Complexity  : Medium — requires bundling reveal.js assets or CDN configuration

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FORMAT-04: Beamer PDF Slides (Priority P2)
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Rationale   : Academic and scientific presentations in PDF format via LaTeX
              Beamer. Pairs with the existing tectonic dependency.
Dependencies: pandoc + tectonic (already required for PDF)
Config type : beamer
Pandoc flags: -t beamer -o output.pdf --pdf-engine=tectonic
Complexity  : Low — reuses existing tectonic infrastructure

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FORMAT-05: Plain Text / Typst (Priority P2)
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Rationale   : Plain text output (.txt) is useful for accessibility, email,
              and terminal contexts. Typst is an emerging alternative to LaTeX
              with simpler syntax and faster compilation.
Dependencies: pandoc (plain text); typst binary (Typst)
Config type : plain / typst
Complexity  : Low (plain text via pandoc); Medium (Typst — new dependency)

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FORMAT-06: ReStructuredText (Priority P3)
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Rationale   : RST is the standard for Python/Sphinx documentation. Renderflow
              could serve as a bridge from Markdown-authored content to
              Sphinx-based documentation sites.
Dependencies: pandoc (already required)
Config type : rst
Pandoc flags: -t rst -o output.rst
Complexity  : Low

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FORMAT-07: Man Page (Priority P3)
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Rationale   : CLI tools with Markdown-authored man pages could use Renderflow
              to produce installable man pages from the same source.
Dependencies: pandoc (already required)
Config type : man
Pandoc flags: -t man -o output.1
Complexity  : Low

================================================================================
6. STRATEGY SYSTEM IMPROVEMENTS
================================================================================

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
6.1 Current Design Assessment
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

The OutputStrategy trait is clean and minimal:

  pub trait OutputStrategy {
      fn render(&self, input: &str, output_path: &str) -> Result<()>;
  }

Strengths:
  - Simple interface; easy to implement new strategies
  - Box<dyn OutputStrategy> enables runtime polymorphism
  - select_strategy() factory centralises strategy selection
  - Template/reference-doc plumbing is consistent across strategies

Weaknesses:
  - input parameter is a string (file path), not a typed document
  - No metadata passed to the strategy (input format, config variables, etc.)
  - Strategy cannot signal partial success or warnings
  - No lifecycle hooks (pre-render validation, post-render cleanup)

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
6.2 Recommended Improvements
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

IMPROVEMENT-S1: Introduce a RenderContext struct
  Pass a typed context object instead of raw strings:

    pub struct RenderContext<'a> {
        pub input_path: &'a str,
        pub input_format: InputFormat,
        pub output_path: &'a str,
        pub variables: &'a HashMap<String, String>,
        pub dry_run: bool,
    }

    pub trait OutputStrategy {
        fn render(&self, ctx: &RenderContext) -> Result<()>;
    }

  This makes the interface stable under future additions (new context fields
  are backward-compatible with a struct, but not with positional arguments).

IMPROVEMENT-S2: Add a validate() lifecycle hook
  Allow strategies to perform pre-render validation (e.g. check tool
  availability, verify template exists) before any I/O begins:

    pub trait OutputStrategy {
        fn validate(&self, ctx: &RenderContext) -> Result<()> { Ok(()) }
        fn render(&self, ctx: &RenderContext) -> Result<()>;
    }

  The build command calls validate() for all strategies upfront (fail-fast),
  then proceeds to render only after all validations pass. This surfaces
  "tectonic not installed" errors before transforms run.

IMPROVEMENT-S3: Composable strategy decorators
  Support wrapping strategies with cross-cutting concerns:

    pub struct PostProcessStrategy<S: OutputStrategy> {
        inner: S,
        post_process: Box<dyn Fn(&str) -> Result<()>>,
    }

  Examples: file size logging, output validation, asset embedding.

IMPROVEMENT-S4: Strategy registry (config-driven selection)
  Replace the match-based select_strategy() with a registry that maps type
  names to factory functions:

    pub struct StrategyRegistry {
        factories: HashMap<String, Box<dyn StrategyFactory>>,
    }

  This enables third-party strategies to be registered without modifying the
  core selector, supporting the plugin system described in Section 9.

================================================================================
7. TRANSFORM SYSTEM IMPROVEMENTS
================================================================================

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
7.1 Current Design Assessment
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

The Transform trait is well-designed:

  pub trait Transform {
      fn name(&self) -> &'static str { "Transform" }
      fn apply(&self, input: String) -> Result<String>;
  }

Registered transforms (in order):
  1. EmojiTransform          — replaces emoji with [emoji]
  2. VariableSubstitutionTransform — {{key}} → value
  3. SyntaxHighlightTransform      — normalise code fence language tags

The TransformRegistry supports fail-fast and continue-on-failure modes,
and logs each transform start/completion at DEBUG level.

Weaknesses:
  - Transforms operate on raw strings; no Markdown AST awareness
  - EmojiTransform is unconditionally lossy (see FINDING-06)
  - Variable substitution corrupts code blocks (see FINDING-08)
  - No output-format-aware transforms (HTML-only vs. all-format transforms)
  - Plugin/extension point not exposed (see FINDING-04)

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
7.2 Recommended Missing Transforms
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

TRANSFORM-01: FootnoteExpansionTransform
  Expand custom footnote syntax (e.g. [^1]: ...) or cross-references before
  passing to pandoc. Pandoc handles standard Markdown footnotes, but custom
  extensions benefit from pre-processing.

TRANSFORM-02: FrontMatterStripTransform
  Strip or extract YAML front matter (---) from the document before rendering.
  Pandoc handles front matter via --metadata-file, but separating it at the
  transform layer enables variable injection from front matter keys.

TRANSFORM-03: IncludeDirectiveTransform
  Support file include directives (e.g. !include path/to/file.md) for
  composing large documents from smaller fragments. This is a frequently
  requested feature in documentation tooling.

TRANSFORM-04: DiagramAsCodeTransform
  Transform fenced code blocks annotated with diagram languages (mermaid,
  plantuml, graphviz) into embedded image references before pandoc rendering.
  Requires calling the respective CLI tools as subprocesses.

TRANSFORM-05: OutputFormatFilterTransform
  A meta-transform that wraps other transforms and applies them only for
  specific output formats (e.g. apply EmojiTransform only for PDF/LaTeX,
  not for HTML where emoji render natively):

    pub struct FormatFilterTransform {
        inner: Box<dyn Transform>,
        formats: Vec<OutputType>,
    }

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
7.3 Plugin System Design
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Near-term (configuration-driven):
  Allow external transform binaries to be registered via renderflow.yaml:

    transforms:
      - name: "custom-preprocessor"
        command: "./scripts/preprocess.sh"
        on_error: continue   # or: fail

  The build command wraps each command in a ShellTransform that pipes the
  document content through stdin/stdout, enabling arbitrary preprocessing
  without requiring Rust code.

Long-term (Rust dynamic linking or WASM):
  Expose a stable ABI for Transform implementations via a plugin crate:

    renderflow-plugin = { version = "0.1", path = "./renderflow-plugin" }

  Transform implementations in external crates are loaded via dynamic
  linking (libloading) or compiled to WASM and run in a sandboxed executor.
  WASM sandboxing is preferred for security isolation.

================================================================================
8. PERFORMANCE & SCALABILITY
================================================================================

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
8.1 Caching
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

CACHE-01: Transform result caching (immediate win)
  The transform pipeline produces identical output for the same (input,
  variables) pair regardless of output format. Cache the transformed content
  string before the per-format loop:

    // In commands/build.rs — before the output format loop
    let registry = register_transforms(&config.variables);
    let transformed = registry.apply_all(normalized_content.clone())?;

    for output in &config.outputs {
        // Use pre-computed `transformed` — no re-running transforms
    }

  This is a one-line refactor that eliminates O(n_formats) redundant work.
  (Note: this applies when all formats share the same transform pipeline;
  format-specific transforms would require per-format caching.)

CACHE-02: Input file content caching
  When Renderflow is used in watch mode (future), the input file hash should
  be compared to the previous render's input hash. If unchanged, skip the
  full pipeline. A simple content hash (e.g. FxHasher or blake3) cached to
  a .renderflow-cache file in the output directory is sufficient.

CACHE-03: Pandoc invocation caching
  Pandoc is deterministic for the same (input content, flags) pair. Cache the
  output file hash alongside the input hash. Skip re-rendering if the input
  hash matches the cached value.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
8.2 Parallelism
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

PARALLEL-01: Parallel output format rendering (high impact)
  Render independent output formats concurrently using Rayon or Tokio:

    use rayon::prelude::*;
    config.outputs.par_iter().map(|output| {
        render_output(output, &transformed, &output_dir, &input_stem)
    }).collect::<Result<Vec<_>>>()?;

  This reduces total render time from sum(format_times) to max(format_times)
  for independent formats. For a typical html+pdf+docx config this is a 2-3×
  speedup for the I/O-bound pandoc invocations.
  Note: The progress bar (indicatif) requires thread-safe updating (MultiBar).

PARALLEL-02: Parallel asset path resolution
  normalize_asset_paths() resolves each image path sequentially with
  filesystem stat() calls. For documents with many images, these can be
  parallelised with Rayon.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
8.3 Pipeline Optimisations
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

OPTIM-01: Single pandoc AST pass for multiple outputs
  pandoc can emit its internal AST as JSON (--to json). A future architecture
  could:
    1. Parse input → pandoc JSON AST (once)
    2. Apply AST-level transforms (reusable across outputs)
    3. Convert AST → each output format (pandoc --from json -t html/pdf/docx)
  This eliminates repeated pandoc parsing and enables richer semantic
  transforms that operate on document structure rather than raw text.

OPTIM-02: Lazy template loading
  init_tera() loads all templates at startup. For configs that use only one
  template, loading all templates is wasteful. Lazy loading (load on first
  access per template name) would reduce startup time for multi-template
  directories.

================================================================================
9. CODE QUALITY & REFACTORING
================================================================================

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
9.1 Dead Code / Unused API
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

REFACTOR-01: Remove or integrate PandocStep
  src/pipeline/pandoc_step.rs defines PandocStep but it is not used by the
  build command or any test. Either:
    Option A: Remove PandocStep entirely (strategies subsume its role)
    Option B: Refactor HtmlStrategy/PdfStrategy/DocxStrategy to use PandocStep
              internally, making pandoc invocation a single reusable step
  Recommendation: Option B eliminates duplicated pandoc arg-building logic
  across the three strategy implementations.

REFACTOR-02: Unify transform entry point
  The build command bypasses Pipeline::run_transforms() and calls
  TransformRegistry::apply_all() directly. Unify these by either:
    Option A: Have Pipeline hold a TransformRegistry (not Vec<Box<dyn Transform>>)
              and delegate run_transforms() to registry.apply_all()
    Option B: Remove Pipeline::run_transforms() and document that callers
              create and run a TransformRegistry independently

REFACTOR-03: Extract pandoc arg construction into a shared helper
  All three strategies (Html, Pdf, Docx) build a Vec<&str> of pandoc arguments
  with similar patterns (--from, input, -o, output, optional --template).
  Extract a PandocArgs builder:

    pub struct PandocArgs { ... }
    impl PandocArgs {
        pub fn new(from: InputFormat, input: &str, output: &str) -> Self
        pub fn with_template(mut self, path: &str) -> Self
        pub fn with_pdf_engine(mut self, engine: &str) -> Self
        pub fn build(self) -> Vec<String>
    }

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
9.2 Better Patterns
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

REFACTOR-04: Make fail_fast configurable from renderflow.yaml
  The TransformRegistry supports fail_fast = false but the build command
  always uses the default (true). Expose this as a config option:

    fail_fast: false   # optional, default true

REFACTOR-05: Typed output filename construction
  The output filename is currently built with string formatting:
    format!("{}/{}.{}", output_dir.display(), input_stem, format)
  This is fragile and does not use std::path::PathBuf composition. Replace
  with:
    output_dir.join(format!("{}.{}", input_stem, format_ext))

REFACTOR-06: EmojiTransform — make output format aware
  Apply the EmojiTransform only for output formats that cannot render emoji
  natively (pdf, latex, docx). For html, pass emoji through unchanged.
  This requires passing the target OutputType through the transform context
  or using the FormatFilterTransform wrapper (see TRANSFORM-05).

================================================================================
10. DOCUMENTATION & DEVELOPER EXPERIENCE
================================================================================

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
10.1 README Assessment
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Strengths:
  - Clear quick-start section with minimal example
  - Architecture diagram shows two-phase pipeline
  - Roadmap communicates planned features
  - Badge links to CI and license

Gaps:
  DOC-01: DOCX is implemented but not listed in the Supported Output Types
          table or Features section. The Roadmap still shows DOCX as pending.

  DOC-02: The transform pipeline is described as "Pluggable in-memory content
          transforms" but the three registered transforms (emoji, variable,
          syntax highlight) are not documented. Users need to know that
          {{variable}} substitution and emoji handling happen automatically.

  DOC-03: The `variables` config key is not documented in the Configuration
          section. A user who reads the README cannot discover how to pass
          variables to their templates.

  DOC-04: The `fail_fast` configuration option (even if not yet exposed in YAML)
          and the continue-on-error transform mode are not documented.

  DOC-05: Dependencies (pandoc, tectonic) are mentioned in the Installation
          section but not with version requirements. If a user has an older
          pandoc that lacks a flag Renderflow uses, the error will be cryptic.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
10.2 CLI Usability
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  CLI-01: The --verbose and --debug flags affect log level but log output goes
          to stdout by default (tracing_subscriber::fmt). Production users may
          prefer structured JSON logs (tracing-subscriber's json feature) for
          log aggregation pipelines. Consider adding --log-format json.

  CLI-02: There is no --output-dir flag to override the YAML config's
          output_dir at the command line. A common workflow is to run the
          same config against different output directories (staging vs. prod).

  CLI-03: The error output for missing pandoc is clear in the strategies, but
          the top-level error for a missing pandoc binary (when HtmlStrategy
          calls run_command) produces a generic "Failed to render HTML output"
          message. Adding a "Check that pandoc is installed" note for NotFound
          errors would improve DX (similar to PdfStrategy::check_tectonic()).

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
10.3 Developer Experience
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  DX-01: The Taskfile.yml is present but not documented in the README. A new
         contributor who finds the Taskfile tasks (task build, task test) will
         have a better experience than one who uses cargo commands directly.

  DX-02: Integration tests that require pandoc are marked #[ignore]. There is
         no task or CI job that runs the full test suite including ignored tests
         with pandoc available. A separate CI job or Taskfile task
         (task test:full) would clarify which tests need external tools.

  DX-03: No CONTRIBUTING.md or development setup guide. For a project that
         intends to be extensible (plugin system, additional formats), a
         contributing guide is important for community engagement.

================================================================================
11. FUTURE ARCHITECTURE RECOMMENDATIONS
================================================================================

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
11.1 Plugin System
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Phase 1 — Shell plugin (near term, low complexity):
  Support external transform commands in renderflow.yaml:

    transforms:
      - name: "diagram-preprocessor"
        command: "npx mermaid-filter"
        on_error: fail

  Implement ShellTransform that pipes document content through the command
  via stdin/stdout. This enables user-defined preprocessing without Rust.

Phase 2 — WASM plugin (medium term, sandboxed):
  Compile Transform implementations to WebAssembly (wasm32-wasi target).
  Load via wasmtime or wasmer. The WASM sandbox prevents plugins from
  accessing the filesystem or network arbitrarily. Plugin authors write
  Rust (or any WASM-targeting language) against the renderflow-plugin crate.

Phase 3 — Crate plugin (long term, performance):
  For high-performance or stateful transforms, expose a stable ABI via
  libloading. This is the fastest option but requires careful ABI stability
  management.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
11.2 Template System Expansion
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  TEMPLATE-01: Unified template registry
    Create a TemplateRegistry that abstracts over Tera (HTML), pandoc LaTeX
    templates (PDF), pandoc reference docs (DOCX), and CSS (EPUB). The registry
    validates all configured templates upfront, regardless of type.

  TEMPLATE-02: Template inheritance and composition
    Tera already supports template inheritance ({% extends %}). Expose this
    to users by documenting base templates and block-override patterns.

  TEMPLATE-03: Built-in theme library
    Ship a curated set of built-in themes (academic, technical, minimal,
    corporate) as template files in the renderflow binary or as a separate
    themes crate. Users select themes by name rather than by path.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
11.3 Agent Integration
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  AGENT-01: Renderflow as an MCP tool
    Expose Renderflow as a Model Context Protocol (MCP) tool so that LLM
    agents can invoke document rendering as a structured tool call:

      Tool name: renderflow.render
      Input: { config_yaml: string, input_content: string }
      Output: { outputs: [{ format: string, content: base64 }] }

    This enables agents to render documents as part of longer workflows
    (e.g. generate → render → publish) without shell subprocess invocations.

  AGENT-02: Config generation assistant
    A companion CLI command (renderflow init) that prompts the user for
    their document type, desired output formats, and available tools, then
    generates a renderflow.yaml. This reduces onboarding friction.

  AGENT-03: Audit command
    Formalise the audit process as a first-class CLI command:
    renderflow audit [--output audits/] [--format log|json|markdown]

    The command analyses the current renderflow.yaml, checks tool availability,
    validates templates, and writes a structured audit report. This audit log
    itself would serve as a worked example of the feature.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
11.4 Multi-Format Orchestration
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  ORCH-01: Pipeline DAG (directed acyclic graph)
    For complex workflows (md → docx → pdf, or md → html → embed-assets →
    pdf), model the pipeline as a DAG where each node is a format conversion
    and edges define data flow. This enables multi-step conversion chains and
    fan-out/fan-in patterns.

  ORCH-02: Watch mode with incremental rebuilds
    Monitor input files with notify (file system event library). On change,
    re-run only the affected pipeline stages. Cache hashes to skip unchanged
    outputs.

  ORCH-03: Remote rendering / distributed pipeline
    For large document sets (e.g. a multi-chapter book), distribute rendering
    across worker processes or remote machines. Each worker renders one chapter;
    results are collected and assembled. gRPC or a simple HTTP API over the
    Renderflow binary would enable this.

